      "The fundamental difference is simple: double glazing uses two panes of glass separated by a gas-filled cavity, while triple glazing adds a third pane and a second cavity. This extra layer reduces thermal transmittance, measured as the U-value. A typical modern double-glazed unit achieves a U-value around 1.2 W/m²K, while a high-specification triple-glazed unit can reach 0.8 W/m²K or lower. In Scotland\'s climate, that 0.4 difference is meaningful over the lifetime of the window.",
      "However, U-value is not the only consideration. Triple glazing is heavier, which places greater demands on the window frame and hardware. Not all frame systems are rated for triple-glazed unit weights, particularly in older properties where the original frames were designed for single glazing. At Alumise, we manufacture <a href=\"/materials/aluminium\">thermally broken aluminium systems</a> with reinforced hardware specifically engineered for triple-glazed units up to 50kg per sash.",
      "Acoustic performance is where triple glazing often surprises homeowners. The additional pane and asymmetric cavity construction significantly reduce external noise transmission. For Edinburgh properties near main roads, railways, or flight paths, this can be a compelling benefit even before thermal savings are considered. Our acoustic triple-glazed systems reduce external noise by up to 40dB, turning a noisy urban environment into a peaceful interior space.",
      "Cost is the obvious barrier. Triple glazing typically adds 30 to 40 percent to the window cost compared to equivalent double glazing. For a full-house replacement of twelve windows, that could mean an additional £3,000 to £5,000. The payback period through energy savings depends on your current heating system, insulation levels, and energy tariffs, but most homeowners in Scotland see a payback period of fifteen to twenty years.",
      "That said, payback period is not the only metric. Comfort is harder to quantify but equally important. Triple glazing virtually eliminates cold draughts near windows and reduces condensation risk on the inner pane. In north-facing rooms or properties exposed to prevailing winds, the difference in comfort is immediately noticeable. For many of our customers in exposed coastal locations like North Berwick or Dunbar, triple glazing is chosen primarily for comfort rather than financial return.",
      "Solar gain is one factor where double glazing can actually outperform triple glazing. The extra pane in a triple unit reduces the amount of solar heat entering the home. For south-facing rooms in Edinburgh that benefit from passive solar heating, high-performance double glazing with low-E coatings and warm-edge spacers can be the more balanced choice, offering excellent insulation without sacrificing free heat from the sun.",
